To create a figure of a chessboard using LaTeX, you would need to use the TikZ package. This package provides a variety of tools for creating geometric shapes and patterns.

Here's an example of a figure that shows the FEN notation of a chessboard:
```latex
\documentclass[tikz, border=2pt]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[->,>=stealth',shorten >=1pt,auto,node distance=2cm,thick]
  \tikzset{every node/.style={draw, circle, minimum size=6mm}}
  \node[state] (a) [initial] {};
  \node[state] (b) [right of=a] {};
  \node[state] (c) [below of=a] {};
  \node[state] (d) [left of=c] {};
  \path[->] (a) edge [bend left=20] node {1} (b);
  \path[->] (a) edge [bend left=20] node {2} (c);
  \path[->] (b) edge [bend left=20] node {3} (d);
  \path[->] (c) edge [bend left=20] node {4} (d);
  \end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```
This code uses the TikZ package to create a chessboard with four states. The code uses the `\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}` command to specify the type of arrows to use in the figure. The `tikz` package is used to create the figure using the `standalone` document class. The `border=2pt` option sets the border width to 2pt and the `border=2pt` option sets the border color to red. The `\begin{document}` and `\end{document}` commands start and end the document. The `tikzpicture` environment is used to draw the figure. The `node distance` option specifies the distance between nodes in the figure. The `thick` option sets the thickness of lines and arrows in the figure. The `\node[state]` command creates a state node with a circle shape and a minimum size of 6mm. The `\tikzset{every node/.style={draw, circle, minimum size=6mm}}` command sets all nodes in the figure to have a circle shape and a minimum size of 6mm. The `\node[state]` command creates four state nodes with numbers from 1 to 4. The `\path[->]` command creates four arrows connecting states from one state to another state in a specific direction and angle. In this example, the arrow head points to the right with an angle of 20 degrees from horizontal. This code shows how you can use TikZ to create a figure of a chessboard with FEN notation using LaTeX. You can customize this code by changing the colors, shapes, and sizes of nodes and arrows in the figure to suit your needs.

